# Main functions

## 1. Find node by id

```js
function getNode(id) {
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}
```

---

## 2. Physics update for nodes

Equivalent cleaned-up version:

```js
function updateNodes() {
  // Pairwise attraction between all nodes
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (let j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      const dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      const dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;

      const force = config.attraction / (dist * dist);
      const fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      const fy = (dy / dist) * force;

      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }

  // Spring constraints
  for (let i = 0; i < links.length; i++) {
    const n1 = getNode(links[i].a);
    const n2 = getNode(links[i].b);
    if (!n1 || !n2) continue;

    const dx = n2.x - n1.x;
    const dy = n2.y - n1.y;
    const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;

    const stretch = dist - links[i].rest;
    const force = (links[i].k || config.springCoeff) * stretch;

    n1.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    n1.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    n2.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    n2.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }

  // Damping, center pull, integrate position
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    nodes[i].vx += (400 - nodes[i].x) * config.centerBias;
    nodes[i].vy += (300 - nodes[i].y) * config.centerBias;

    nodes[i].vx *= config.amplification;
    nodes[i].vy *= config.amplification;

    nodes[i].x += nodes[i].vx;
    nodes[i].y += nodes[i].vy;
  }
}
```

### Important note
The “attraction” math actually pushes nodes in the direction of `(node[i] - node[j])`, so depending on sign interpretation you might call it attraction/repulsion-ish force logic. But because springs and center bias are also present, the overall effect is a floating graph layout.

---

## 3. Spawn particles

```js
function spawnParticle() {
  if (stream.length >= config.streamLimit) return;

  const node = nodes[Math.floor(Math.random() * nodes.length)];
  const angle = Math.random() * TAU;
  const speed = 0.3 + Math.random() * SQRT1_2;

  stream.push({
    x: node.x,
    y: node.y,
    vx: Math.cos(angle) * speed,
    vy: Math.sin(angle) * speed,
    age: 0,
    maxAge: 800 + Math.random() * 1200,
    size: 0.8 + (Math.random() * PHI) * SQRT1_2
  });
}
```

This creates a particle at a random node with random direction, speed, lifetime, and size.

---

## 4. Update particles

```js
function updateParticles() {
  for (let i = stream.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    const p = stream[i];

    p.age++;
    p.x += p.vx;
    p.y += p.vy;

    p.vx *= 1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125;
    p.vy *= 1 - config.streamDecay * 0.125;

    if (p.age > p.maxAge) {
      stream.splice(i, 1);
    }
  }
}
```

Particles slowly drift and lose speed, then disappear when too old.

---

## 5. Update camera

```js
function updateCamera() {
  camera.x += (cameraTarget.x - camera.x) * config.theta;
  camera.y += (cameraTarget.y - camera.y) * config.theta;
  camera.zoom += (cameraTarget.zoom - camera.zoom) * config.theta;
}
```

Smooth interpolation / easing.

---

## 6. Main tick

```js
function tickFrame() {
  updateNodes();
  updateParticles();
  updateCamera();

  if (tick % 3 === 0) spawnParticle();
  tick++;
}

setInterval(tickFrame, 10);
```

So:

- physics updates every 10 ms
- particle emitted every 3 ticks ≈ every 30 ms

